T1  - Differentiation Within An Organizational Population: Additional Evidence from The Wine Industry
AU  - Swaminathan, Anand
AU  - Delacroix, Jacques
Y1  - 1991/09/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256411
DO  - 10.5465/256411
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 679
EP  - 692
VL  - 34
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this study of California wineries observed between 1940 and 1984, we showed that organizations within a population may escape competitive pressures through differentiation. Both wineries founded in the table wine niche and those that diversified into it were subject to lower failure rates than other wineries. This study also demonstrated how it is possible to compensate for a lack of strictly appropriate data, a characteristic of ecological studies.
AB  - In this study of California wineries observed between 1940 and 1984, we showed that organizations within a population may escape competitive pressures through differentiation. Both wineries founded in the table wine niche and those that diversified into it were subject to lower failure rates than other wineries. This study also demonstrated how it is possible to compensate for a lack of strictly appropriate data, a characteristic of ecological studies.
